<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-11-20">
  <title>Resources for 11/20</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize what a <em>polynomial function</em> <m>f(x)</m> approaches as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize what a polynomial function <m>f(x)</m> approaches as <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Identify all <m>x</m>-intercepts of the graph of a polynomial expressed in factored form.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-poly-end-behavior-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Polynomial End Behavior (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on the end behavior of <em>polynomials</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="7HI-K7weJQs" />

    <problem>
      <title>Polynomial End Behavior (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        For each of the following, determine what happens to the function as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> and as <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>.  Explain what this means about what the graph looks like.  Note that <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> are all constants.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=ax^2+bx+c</m>.  Hint:  The answer will depend on <m>a</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^3+bx^2+cx+d</m>.  Hint:  Factor out <m>x^3</m> from every term.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^4+bx^3+cx^2+dx+e</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = ax^5+bx^4+cx^3+dx^2+ex+f</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your observations above to determine the end behavior of <m>f(x) = -2(x-a)(x-b)(x-c)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-desmos-sliders">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Using Sliders in Desmos</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on using <em>sliders</em> in Desmos to help us understand roots of polynomials. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="38a__ucpIX0" />

    <problem>
      <title>Exploring Polynomial Roots and Graphs (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        Plug the following functions into Desmos, making a slider for each coefficient (i.e. <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, etc).  Play with different values of the coefficients to see the minimum and maximum number of <m>x</m>-intercepts of the function (i.e. values of <m>x</m> where the function has an output of 0).
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x)=ax+b</m>, <m>a \ne 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = cx^2+dx+e</m>, <m>c \ne 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = gx^3+hx^2+ix+j</m>, <m>g \ne 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f(x) = kx^4+\ell x^3 + mx^2+nx+p</m>, <m>k \ne 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 5.2: pp. 262-271
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-poly-polynomials.html">HTML version of Section 5.2</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>